WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:08.160
[Amit Varma]: Before you listen to this episode of The Scene and the Unseen, I have a recommendation for

00:00:08.160 --> 00:00:09.160
[Amit Varma]: you.

00:00:09.160 --> 00:00:13.280
[Amit Varma]: Do check out Pulya Bazi, hosted by Saurabh Chandra and Pranay Kotesane, two really good

00:00:13.280 --> 00:00:14.280
[Amit Varma]: friends of mine.

00:00:14.280 --> 00:00:18.400
[Amit Varma]: Kick-ass podcast in Hindi, it's amazing.

00:00:18.400 --> 00:00:21.240
[Amit Varma]: A few days ago, my aunt in the US wrote to me.

00:00:21.240 --> 00:00:25.280
[Amit Varma]: She is visiting India at the end of January, after many years, and wanted to know what

00:00:25.280 --> 00:00:27.040
[Amit Varma]: gift I wanted from there.

00:00:27.040 --> 00:00:30.800
[Amit Varma]: I assured her that I wanted nothing, but she insisted, saying that she was going to get

00:00:30.800 --> 00:00:34.840
[Amit Varma]: me a gift anyway, and it might as well be something I wanted that I could not get in

00:00:34.840 --> 00:00:35.840
[Amit Varma]: India.

00:00:35.840 --> 00:00:37.160
[Amit Varma]: That got me thinking.

00:00:37.160 --> 00:00:42.440
[Amit Varma]: I grew up as a kid in the 1980s, and in those days when our relatives visited from America,

00:00:42.440 --> 00:00:46.080
[Amit Varma]: they would come laden with unimaginable, almost magical goodies.

00:00:46.080 --> 00:00:48.680
[Amit Varma]: There was so much that you did not get in India.

00:00:48.680 --> 00:00:53.080
[Amit Varma]: But now, wracking my brains, I couldn't think of anything that I could not get here.

00:00:53.080 --> 00:00:57.720
[Amit Varma]: Clothes, electronics, perfumes, books, music, and everything is available here.

00:00:57.720 --> 00:01:01.880
[Amit Varma]: Finally, I asked my aunt to get me some assault rifles.

00:01:01.880 --> 00:01:06.160
[Amit Varma]: But in a larger sense, this got me to thinking how much my world has changed.

00:01:06.160 --> 00:01:09.480
[Amit Varma]: Back in the day, we used to scramble even to listen to good music.

00:01:09.480 --> 00:01:13.920
[Amit Varma]: We'd spend days sourcing music and getting mixtapes made, and every new song we gathered

00:01:13.920 --> 00:01:14.920
[Amit Varma]: was like a treasure.

00:01:14.920 --> 00:01:19.320
[Amit Varma]: We had limited ways of watching movies from around the world, and I remember how eagerly

00:01:19.320 --> 00:01:24.480
[Amit Varma]: we tuned in to watch the one eclectic film per week that Doordarshan showed in a late

00:01:24.480 --> 00:01:25.680
[Amit Varma]: night slot.

00:01:25.680 --> 00:01:29.720
[Amit Varma]: People often speak of how the film, in which Annie gives it those ones, was shown only

00:01:29.720 --> 00:01:31.120
[Amit Varma]: once on Indian television.

00:01:31.120 --> 00:01:35.600
[Amit Varma]: Well, I remember watching it that one time, as I am sure do many other Indian kids my

00:01:35.600 --> 00:01:36.600
[Amit Varma]: age.

00:01:36.600 --> 00:01:37.600
[Amit Varma]: There was nothing else.

00:01:37.600 --> 00:01:42.100
[Amit Varma]: Today, we can play any song we want to on Google Play or Amazon Prime or Apple Music.

00:01:42.100 --> 00:01:46.920
[Amit Varma]: We can stream a whole world of movies, and the technology on our phone today is the science

00:01:46.920 --> 00:01:48.520
[Amit Varma]: fiction of yesterday.

00:01:48.520 --> 00:01:52.680
[Amit Varma]: I think it was my friend Uday Shankar who once said that the next generation will not

00:01:52.680 --> 00:01:55.760
[Amit Varma]: know what it is like to get lost.

00:01:55.760 --> 00:01:56.760
[Amit Varma]: That's right.

00:01:56.760 --> 00:01:57.760
[Amit Varma]: GPS Zindabad.

00:01:57.760 --> 00:01:59.880
[Amit Varma]: Though as a caveat, battery is Murdabad.

00:01:59.880 --> 00:02:04.360
[Amit Varma]: But battery life aside, our lives are just bloody astonishing.

00:02:04.360 --> 00:02:20.680
[Unknown]: And we take all this progress for granted.

00:02:20.680 --> 00:02:22.040
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to the scene in the unseen.

00:02:22.040 --> 00:02:26.480
[Amit Varma]: My guest today is Steven Pinker, who I regard as one of the great public intellectuals of

00:02:26.480 --> 00:02:30.080
[Amit Varma]: our times, and someone who's been a huge personal influence on me.

00:02:30.080 --> 00:02:34.780
[Amit Varma]: My favorite book by Pinker is The Blank Slate, which shone a light on what exactly human

00:02:34.780 --> 00:02:40.480
[Amit Varma]: nature is and where it comes from, and gave me a deep sense of the contingency of my existence

00:02:40.480 --> 00:02:43.040
[Amit Varma]: and my personality and my identity.

00:02:43.040 --> 00:02:48.000
[Amit Varma]: All that is a recipe for humility, but it also gave me a sense of awe and wonder at

00:02:48.000 --> 00:02:51.160
[Amit Varma]: the complexity of the machinery in our brains.

00:02:51.160 --> 00:02:55.800
[Amit Varma]: But the book that is the subject of this episode is his latest book Enlightenment Now, which

00:02:55.800 --> 00:03:01.400
[Amit Varma]: demonstrates using exhaustive data, how the world has gotten better across every metric

00:03:01.400 --> 00:03:06.560
[Amit Varma]: that we can possibly think of, and how we need to respect enlightenment values if we

00:03:06.560 --> 00:03:09.920
[Amit Varma]: are to preserve and enhance this fragile progress.

00:03:09.920 --> 00:03:13.920
[Amit Varma]: I met Steven at the sidelines of the recent Times Literary Festival in Mumbai, and we

00:03:13.920 --> 00:03:17.520
[Amit Varma]: recorded in a makeshift studio we set up at the venue.

00:03:17.520 --> 00:03:20.520
[Amit Varma]: So please do excuse us for any sound disturbances.

00:03:20.520 --> 00:03:24.160
