00:29:41.720 --> 00:29:46.760
[Amit Varma]: Steven, in your chapter about the environment, which is something that people have great

00:29:46.760 --> 00:29:52.960
[Amit Varma]: legitimate worries about, and there's a great quote by Stewart Brand, quote, no product

00:29:52.960 --> 00:29:56.840
[Amit Varma]: of agriculture is the slightest bit natural to an ecologist.

00:29:56.840 --> 00:30:00.880
[Amit Varma]: You take a nice complex ecosystem, chop it into rectangles, clear it to the ground and

00:30:00.880 --> 00:30:04.340
[Amit Varma]: hammer it into perpetual early succession.

00:30:04.340 --> 00:30:08.400
[Amit Varma]: You bust it, sort, flatten it wide and drench it with vast quantities of constant water.

00:30:08.400 --> 00:30:12.740
[Amit Varma]: Then you populate it with uniform monochips of profoundly damaged plants incapable of

00:30:12.740 --> 00:30:14.080
[Amit Varma]: living on their own.

00:30:14.080 --> 00:30:19.260
[Amit Varma]: Every food plant is a pathetic, narrow specialist in one skill inbred for thousands of years

00:30:19.260 --> 00:30:21.640
[Amit Varma]: to a state of genetic idiocy.

00:30:21.640 --> 00:30:26.880
[Amit Varma]: These plants are so fragile, they had to domesticate humans just to take endless care of them,

00:30:26.880 --> 00:30:27.880
[Amit Varma]: unquote.

00:30:27.880 --> 00:30:30.880
[Amit Varma]: And yet everybody wants organic food, naturally grown food.

00:30:30.880 --> 00:30:36.120
[Guest]: Yes, and organic food is terrible for the environment because it uses so much more land.

00:30:36.120 --> 00:30:42.280
[Guest]: That was Stewart Brand, who is kind of a hero to the counterculture and the whole organic,

00:30:42.280 --> 00:30:47.200
[Guest]: small movement in the 1970s when he published the famous book The Whole Earth Catalog, often

00:30:47.200 --> 00:30:53.720
[Guest]: considered a predecessor of the World Wide Web, although it was on paper, and he changed

00:30:53.720 --> 00:30:54.720
[Guest]: his mind.

00:30:54.720 --> 00:30:58.960
[Guest]: He's an environmental activist and in his book Whole Earth Discipline, he helped found

00:30:58.960 --> 00:31:04.920
[Guest]: the movement of eco-modernism by arguing that what's best for the environment is density,

00:31:04.920 --> 00:31:09.480
[Guest]: is people having less of a footprint on the environment and that includes growing more

00:31:09.480 --> 00:31:12.680
[Guest]: food on less land.

00:31:12.680 --> 00:31:16.160
[Amit Varma]: And for those who worry that the environment is getting worse, you also talk about the

00:31:16.160 --> 00:31:22.640
[Amit Varma]: environmental Kuznets curve, where things appear to get worse as far as the environment

00:31:22.640 --> 00:31:27.600
[Amit Varma]: is concerned, but after a while, when societies get more prosperous and they start caring

00:31:27.600 --> 00:31:31.240
[Amit Varma]: more about the air around them, it gets better again.

00:31:31.240 --> 00:31:32.560
[Guest]: That is a general trend.

00:31:32.560 --> 00:31:37.720
[Guest]: It doesn't happen by itself as no kind of progress happens by itself, but as countries

00:31:37.720 --> 00:31:43.000
[Guest]: do get more developed and richer, they devote more of their resources to protecting the

00:31:43.000 --> 00:31:50.120
[Guest]: environment, to pollution control devices, to laws and enforcing those laws.

00:31:50.120 --> 00:31:52.560
[Guest]: And their citizens' values change.

00:31:52.560 --> 00:31:57.100
[Guest]: If the main thing you're worried about is getting electricity and you can put up with

00:31:57.100 --> 00:32:01.800
[Guest]: a certain amount of environmental damage, your top priority is cooking your food and

00:32:01.800 --> 00:32:06.640
[Guest]: heating your home and lighting your lights, even to the point that the worst forms of

00:32:06.640 --> 00:32:11.600
[Guest]: pollution are those suffered by poor countries, such as indoor cooking smoke, such as contaminated

00:32:11.600 --> 00:32:12.880
[Guest]: water.

00:32:12.880 --> 00:32:17.960
[Guest]: As countries get wealthier, they can devote their attention to the worst kinds of pollution,

00:32:17.960 --> 00:32:26.000
[Guest]: namely indoor cooking smoke and contaminated water, but also to the cleanliness of their

00:32:26.000 --> 00:32:33.440
[Guest]: harbors and rivers and atmosphere, and they can start enforcing laws to curb pollution.

00:32:33.440 --> 00:32:40.280
[Guest]: This is certainly obvious to an American visiting Mumbai, as we are now, where looking out the

00:32:40.280 --> 00:32:45.000
[Guest]: window we can barely see the skyline of the city just a couple of miles away because of

00:32:45.000 --> 00:32:49.280
[Guest]: the thick smog, which you never see in an American city, although of course American

00:32:49.280 --> 00:32:57.240
[Guest]: cities in the 1950s and the 1960s were notorious for their smog, but then because of technology

00:32:57.240 --> 00:33:02.360
[Guest]: and laws and regulations, American and European cities have managed to bring the rate of air

00:33:02.360 --> 00:33:04.480
[Amit Varma]: pollution considerably down.

00:33:04.480 --> 00:33:07.280
[Amit Varma]: If you think Bombay is bad, you should go to Delhi.

00:33:07.280 --> 00:33:08.280
[Guest]: So I've heard.

00:33:08.280 --> 00:33:13.880
[Amit Varma]: You also talk about how sort of technology, we kind of take technology for granted and

00:33:13.880 --> 00:33:17.840
[Amit Varma]: assume when we are extrapolating for the future that it's going to stay as it is, but we keep

00:33:17.840 --> 00:33:18.840
[Amit Varma]: innovating.

00:33:18.840 --> 00:33:23.560
[Amit Varma]: Like you point out how throughout history there's been this process of decarbonization.

00:33:23.560 --> 00:33:28.020
[Amit Varma]: To quote again from your book, quote, the oldest hydrocarbon fuel, dry wood, has a ratio

00:33:28.020 --> 00:33:33.040
[Amit Varma]: of combustible carbon atoms to hydrogen atoms of about 10 to 1.

00:33:33.040 --> 00:33:38.080
[Amit Varma]: The coal which replaced it during the industrial revolution has a ratio of 2 to 1.

00:33:38.080 --> 00:33:41.440
[Amit Varma]: A petroleum fuel such as kerosene may have 1 to 2.

00:33:41.440 --> 00:33:45.200
[Amit Varma]: Natural gas is composed mainly of methane with a ratio of 1 to 4.

00:33:45.200 --> 00:33:49.600
[Amit Varma]: We are just getting better and better and more and more efficient and part of it is

00:33:49.600 --> 00:33:55.540
[Amit Varma]: of course that as the costs of all of those earlier fuels rise, people innovate.

00:33:55.540 --> 00:34:01.480
[Guest]: People innovate and people when they can afford it, they don't want to breathe polluted air

00:34:01.480 --> 00:34:07.360
[Guest]: and they figure out ways of getting the energy they need with less pollution if they recognize

00:34:07.360 --> 00:34:12.400
[Guest]: that pollution is a problem and if they apply their ingenuity to reducing it.

00:34:12.400 --> 00:34:16.880
[Guest]: That could continue with the development of both renewable energy sources like solar and

00:34:16.880 --> 00:34:24.400
[Guest]: wind and the development of nuclear power which another heresy of the eco-modernist

00:34:24.400 --> 00:34:31.280
[Guest]: movement, many eco-modernists are advocates of nuclear power as the most abundant scalable

00:34:31.280 --> 00:34:38.620
[Guest]: form of zero carbon energy even though nuclear has a terrible reputation, actually is extraordinarily

00:34:38.620 --> 00:34:44.680
[Guest]: safe compared to coal and oil and gas which kill far more people every single year and

00:34:44.680 --> 00:34:48.680
[Guest]: of course nuclear power does not generate CO2.

00:34:48.680 --> 00:34:54.680
[Guest]: So it may be that we need within the next couple of decades a whole new generation of

00:34:54.680 --> 00:35:00.720
[Guest]: nuclear technology, so-called fourth generation, small modular reactors that are much less

00:35:00.720 --> 00:35:07.360
[Guest]: expensive, much less prone to accidents than existing reactors and it may be that that

00:35:07.360 --> 00:35:14.800
[Guest]: technology will be the next leap in the process of decarbonization if we encourage it.

00:35:14.800 --> 00:35:18.920
[Amit Varma]: And that also explains why, you know, you make a very convincing case for why nuclear

00:35:18.920 --> 00:35:24.040
[Amit Varma]: energy is something that is unnecessarily given a bad rap and you also talk about the

00:35:24.040 --> 00:35:27.160
[Amit Varma]: false binary between environment and development.

00:35:27.160 --> 00:35:29.160
[Amit Varma]: One did not come at the cost of the other.

00:35:29.160 --> 00:35:35.040
[Guest]: Yes, I mean there are some areas in which there is some tension but with technology,

00:35:35.040 --> 00:35:40.560
[Guest]: with knowledge, we can apply human ingenuity to figure out how to get more human benefits

00:35:40.560 --> 00:35:43.240
[Guest]: with less environmental damage.

00:35:43.240 --> 00:35:47.480
[Guest]: It won't happen by itself, it has to be a goal to reduce the environmental damage but

00:35:47.480 --> 00:35:53.720
[Guest]: that does tend to become a goal as people satisfy their most basic needs, just feeding

00:35:53.720 --> 00:35:57.520
[Guest]: themselves and their children and getting to work and lighting their homes and they

00:35:57.520 --> 00:36:00.200
[Guest]: do tend to be more concerned about the environment.

00:36:00.200 --> 00:36:06.640
[Guest]: No one wants to breathe smog and so they encourage measures that do that.

00:36:06.640 --> 00:36:11.160
[Guest]: In rich countries like the United States and Europe, over the last 40 years at the same

00:36:11.160 --> 00:36:18.040
[Guest]: time as population has grown, GDP has grown, even number of miles has increased but the

00:36:18.040 --> 00:36:21.640
[Guest]: levels of air pollution and water pollution have decreased.

00:36:21.640 --> 00:36:25.360
[Amit Varma]: You know there are a bunch of other chapters where you go through metrics like safety,

00:36:25.360 --> 00:36:29.600
[Amit Varma]: democracy, equal rights, knowledge but since we're running out of time, I'll just skip

00:36:29.600 --> 00:36:33.560
[Amit Varma]: over them, encourage my listeners to sort of just buy the book and read all of them

00:36:33.560 --> 00:36:38.240
[Amit Varma]: and go over to the big questions that are kind of safe for the end.

00:36:38.240 --> 00:36:42.760
[Amit Varma]: Here's one, you know at one point you talk about the post-truth era and I'm quoting from

00:36:42.760 --> 00:36:46.720
[Amit Varma]: you, you say editorialists should retire the new clich that we are in a post-truth era

00:36:46.720 --> 00:36:49.240
[Amit Varma]: unless they can keep up a tone of scatting irony.

00:36:49.240 --> 00:36:53.400
[Amit Varma]: The term is corrosive because it implies that we should resign ourselves to propaganda and

00:36:53.400 --> 00:36:56.000
[Amit Varma]: lies and just fight back with more of our own.

00:36:56.000 --> 00:37:00.600
[Amit Varma]: We are not in a post-truth era, mendacity, truth shading, conspiracy theories, extraordinary

00:37:00.600 --> 00:37:05.440
[Amit Varma]: popular delusions and the madness of crowds are as old as our species and so is the conviction

00:37:05.440 --> 00:37:08.200
[Amit Varma]: that some ideas are right and others are wrong.

00:37:08.200 --> 00:37:14.440
[Amit Varma]: Where I would kind of say that modern times are possibly different because what social

00:37:14.440 --> 00:37:21.080
[Amit Varma]: media does is it pushes us into echo chambers where we are sort of, we find like-minded

00:37:21.080 --> 00:37:26.440
[Amit Varma]: people, we confirm our prejudices, we confirm our biases and within those echo chambers

00:37:26.440 --> 00:37:31.960
[Amit Varma]: is really no talking to each other, you know we just get stuck in those, is that something

00:37:31.960 --> 00:37:33.280
[Amit Varma]: that kind of worries you?

00:37:33.280 --> 00:37:38.960
[Guest]: I mean that does happen although the polarization in the United States was really begun before

00:37:38.960 --> 00:37:40.360
[Unknown]: the advent of social media.

00:37:40.360 --> 00:37:45.920
[Guest]: It was begun in large part by cable news channels and even before that there were right-wing

00:37:45.920 --> 00:37:51.200
[Guest]: magazines and left-wing magazines and right-wing newspapers and left-wing newspapers and the

00:37:51.200 --> 00:37:56.280
[Guest]: thing about the internet is that you're one click away from an opposing viewpoint whereas

00:37:56.280 --> 00:38:00.880
[Guest]: in print media you have to actually go out and buy a newspaper or magazine from the other

00:38:00.880 --> 00:38:03.360
[Guest]: side of the political spectrum.

00:38:03.360 --> 00:38:07.880
[Guest]: So even though there has been a trend toward polarization at least in the United States

00:38:07.880 --> 00:38:15.240
[Guest]: and Europe, I think it's become a lazy habit to blame everything that goes wrong on social

00:38:15.240 --> 00:38:16.240
[Guest]: media.

00:38:16.240 --> 00:38:21.040
[Guest]: I think this process began before social media and it may have occurred even without it.

00:38:21.040 --> 00:38:27.840
[Guest]: I think part of it is driven by the increasing division by education and income where people

00:38:27.840 --> 00:38:34.120
[Guest]: are much more likely to live with people who have the same level of education as they do.

00:38:34.120 --> 00:38:38.840
[Guest]: Neighborhoods have become more segregated by education and education tends to go with

00:38:38.840 --> 00:38:42.280
[Guest]: political opinion or by profession.

00:38:42.280 --> 00:38:47.840
[Guest]: The business people, the doctors and lawyers and professors, the small business owners,

00:38:47.840 --> 00:38:53.400
[Guest]: factory workers tend to live with others of the same type and so some of the residential

00:38:53.400 --> 00:38:56.160
[Guest]: segregation is another factor.

00:38:56.160 --> 00:39:01.320
[Guest]: But social media only became popular starting in the late 2000s so we can't blame things

00:39:01.320 --> 00:39:02.320
[Amit Varma]: that have been going on for decades.

00:39:02.320 --> 00:39:05.600
[Amit Varma]: Well absolutely but there's a theory that for example the rise of Trump in the USA and

00:39:05.600 --> 00:39:10.080
[Amit Varma]: Modi here is partly exacerbated by that because it led to what you would call preference cascades

00:39:10.080 --> 00:39:15.360
[Amit Varma]: where say in the context of India I often say that people who were closeted bigots would

00:39:15.360 --> 00:39:19.520
[Amit Varma]: do preference falsification where they would not express their feelings in public because

00:39:19.520 --> 00:39:23.520
[Amit Varma]: hey it was uncool but suddenly the internet shows them that hey there are a lot of other

00:39:23.520 --> 00:39:28.440
[Amit Varma]: closet bigots out there and they feel validated and empowered by that.

00:39:28.440 --> 00:39:36.200
[Guest]: That is true because even as opinions that used to be taboo are now expressed on social

00:39:36.200 --> 00:39:44.360
[Guest]: media overall worldwide in India, in the United States, everywhere the rate of actual bigotry

00:39:44.360 --> 00:39:45.360
[Guest]: has gone down.

00:39:45.360 --> 00:39:50.680
[Guest]: The rate of sexism, the rate of homophobia but the minority and they still exist who

00:39:50.680 --> 00:39:57.640
[Guest]: are bigoted are able to express their views, find people who are of like minds and therefore

00:39:57.640 --> 00:40:04.240
[Guest]: have a forum for expressing ideas that used to be taboo even if they are becoming numerically

00:40:04.240 --> 00:40:06.760
[Amit Varma]: less common.

00:40:06.760 --> 00:40:11.840
[Amit Varma]: When you were earlier asked at the talk you gave at the Times Lit Fest here about populism

00:40:11.840 --> 00:40:15.240
[Amit Varma]: and you said you were optimistic populism would go away and you gave three reasons for

00:40:15.240 --> 00:40:20.720
[Amit Varma]: that and those reasons were that one older people tend to be populist and they'll die

00:40:20.720 --> 00:40:24.840
[Amit Varma]: off, two it's a factor of education that the more education you have the less populist

00:40:24.840 --> 00:40:31.560
[Amit Varma]: you're likely to be and the third is that the more urbanized you are the less likely

00:40:31.560 --> 00:40:35.520
[Amit Varma]: you are to be populist but I'd actually venture to say that all of these might be true in

00:40:35.520 --> 00:40:36.520
[Amit Varma]: the US.

00:40:36.520 --> 00:40:38.120
[Amit Varma]: It's the exact opposite in India.

00:40:38.120 --> 00:40:44.080
[Amit Varma]: You find that the most populism comes from all the engineers, it's rampant in the cities

00:40:44.080 --> 00:40:48.000
[Amit Varma]: and it's probably more widespread among young people than otherwise.

00:40:48.000 --> 00:40:53.440
[Guest]: Well it's true in the United States, in Europe and in Britain so I don't know about data

00:40:53.440 --> 00:40:54.440
[Guest]: from India.

00:40:54.440 --> 00:40:57.680
[Guest]: So we need to know, it's not a question of whether it's rampant in cities, the question

00:40:57.680 --> 00:41:02.320
[Guest]: is is it more rampant than it is in the more rural areas.

00:41:02.320 --> 00:41:05.600
[Amit Varma]: Right fair enough at some point I'll get you data on that.

00:41:05.600 --> 00:41:11.480
[Amit Varma]: Another interesting thing you sort of talk about is the dangers of tribalism in the academy.

00:41:11.480 --> 00:41:15.000
[Amit Varma]: You know earlier during this conversation you mentioned how Chris Rock when he cracked

00:41:15.000 --> 00:41:19.360
[Amit Varma]: that joke may not be able to get away with it today with all the political correctness

00:41:19.360 --> 00:41:23.520
[Amit Varma]: and you know we know the dangers of the right, what the populists are doing and so on because

00:41:23.520 --> 00:41:28.520
[Amit Varma]: their dangers are you know if they are bigoted they're openly bigoted but what you often

00:41:28.520 --> 00:41:34.960
[Amit Varma]: have from some factions of the far left is that there's a lot of sanctimony which hides

00:41:34.960 --> 00:41:37.880
[Amit Varma]: the identity politics that is playing out.

00:41:37.880 --> 00:41:41.640
[Guest]: I think that is a problem and in fact the two problems are not independent because many

00:41:41.640 --> 00:41:47.960
[Guest]: people who have been attracted to populism list among their top reasons that they are

00:41:47.960 --> 00:41:49.600
[Guest]: sick of political correctness.

00:41:49.600 --> 00:41:53.080
[Guest]: That was the very first thing that Donald Trump said in the very first debate among

00:41:53.080 --> 00:41:59.560
[Guest]: the Republican candidates, he got a huge reaction and it is true that within many mainstream

00:41:59.560 --> 00:42:06.200
[Guest]: publications within universities there are certain, there is definitely a shift toward

00:42:06.200 --> 00:42:15.000
[Guest]: a political left accompanied by a suppression of hypotheses and opinions that don't conform

00:42:15.000 --> 00:42:17.960
[Guest]: to a certain left wing orthodoxy.

00:42:17.960 --> 00:42:25.800
[Guest]: Now of the two polls that we're seeing, the movement to the left in academia and the movement

00:42:25.800 --> 00:42:30.800
[Guest]: to the right in politics, the movement to the right in politics is much more worrying

00:42:30.800 --> 00:42:33.680
[Guest]: because politicians have power and professors don't.

00:42:33.680 --> 00:42:42.400
[Guest]: Nonetheless, since they do feed each other, since I know former students, people who write

00:42:42.400 --> 00:42:47.340
[Guest]: to me who are, they're not idiots, they're intelligent, they're educated but they feel

00:42:47.340 --> 00:42:55.760
[Guest]: so excluded by the confines of left wing political correctness that they are tempted to join

00:42:55.760 --> 00:43:01.400
[Guest]: the right just because they think that's a place where at least the opinions can be expressed.

00:43:01.400 --> 00:43:07.800
[Guest]: So I think that to prevent that from happening, academics should be careful to preserve diversity

00:43:07.800 --> 00:43:14.280
[Guest]: of political backgrounds, expression of ideas even if they're unpopular, the marketplace

00:43:14.280 --> 00:43:15.280
[Guest]: of ideas.

00:43:15.280 --> 00:43:16.280
[Amit Varma]: Right.

00:43:16.280 --> 00:43:20.480
[Amit Varma]: And in your book you make a very strong case for progress, you believe it will continue

00:43:20.480 --> 00:43:22.520
[Amit Varma]: but you don't think it's inevitable.

00:43:22.520 --> 00:43:25.440
[Guest]: What are the threats to humanism?

00:43:25.440 --> 00:43:30.160
[Guest]: Certainly the rise of the whole family of movements that we tend to call authoritarian

00:43:30.160 --> 00:43:31.540
[Guest]: populism.

00:43:31.540 --> 00:43:43.280
[Guest]: These include religious identity, they include ethnic and national chauvinism and jingoism,

00:43:43.280 --> 00:43:50.560
[Guest]: include the cynicism toward institutions such as liberal democracy, regulated markets, international

00:43:50.560 --> 00:43:55.960
[Guest]: organizations like the UN and treaties and international pacts.

00:43:55.960 --> 00:44:05.520
[Guest]: The idea that progress comes from charismatic leaders who authentically voice the soul of

00:44:05.520 --> 00:44:13.720
[Guest]: the people rather than by rules and laws and fiduciary duties and responsibilities that

00:44:13.720 --> 00:44:19.040
[Guest]: are built into the institutions rather than the virtue of the particular people who hold

00:44:19.040 --> 00:44:20.840
[Guest]: those positions of power.

00:44:20.840 --> 00:44:25.640
[Guest]: We see that in the United States and of course in other countries including India and the

00:44:25.640 --> 00:44:31.640
[Guest]: tendency of leaders to try to run around the safeguards written into law simply because

00:44:31.640 --> 00:44:35.240
[Guest]: they are popular, they know the truth, they have the people behind them.

00:44:35.240 --> 00:44:39.720
[Guest]: That of course is the path toward a dictatorship and disaster.

00:44:39.720 --> 00:44:43.880
[Guest]: So all of these trends and they tend to correlate, tends to be some of the same people who believe

00:44:43.880 --> 00:44:47.600
[Guest]: all of them are threats to humanism.

00:44:47.600 --> 00:44:54.680
[Guest]: There's also of course a trend against humanism in more radical forms of Marxism and leftism

00:44:54.680 --> 00:45:01.040
[Guest]: that prioritize the interests of the class above the well-being of individual people

00:45:01.040 --> 00:45:04.920
[Guest]: and that tend to encourage demonization of one class by another.

00:45:04.920 --> 00:45:08.160
[Amit Varma]: And like you point out, one of the strengths of the Enlightenment is that we think in terms

00:45:08.160 --> 00:45:11.800
[Amit Varma]: of individuals rather than groups and or classes of people.

00:45:11.800 --> 00:45:18.400
[Guest]: Yeah, very much and not because of some a priori commitment to individualism but simply

00:45:18.400 --> 00:45:24.380
[Guest]: because it's individuals who can suffer and flourish and feel pleasure and pain.

00:45:24.380 --> 00:45:31.800
[Guest]: Only metaphorically can an entire religion or an entire ethnic group flourish or suffer.

00:45:31.800 --> 00:45:34.520
[Guest]: It's the individual people who actually feel the pain.

00:45:34.520 --> 00:45:35.520
[Amit Varma]: Absolutely.

00:45:35.520 --> 00:45:37.920
[Amit Varma]: So I know you're in a hurry so I'm going to end with one last question and I'm going to

00:45:37.920 --> 00:45:40.240
[Amit Varma]: ask you to be a sport on this.

00:45:40.240 --> 00:45:45.560
[Amit Varma]: In your book you pointed out that students in Talmudic debates are often asked to argue

00:45:45.560 --> 00:45:47.160
[Amit Varma]: the other side.

00:45:47.160 --> 00:45:50.400
[Amit Varma]: So can you tell me briefly why the world is going to hell?

00:45:50.400 --> 00:45:56.160
[Guest]: Well it could if we don't deal with the problem of climate change and things could get a lot

00:45:56.160 --> 00:45:57.320
[Guest]: worse.

00:45:57.320 --> 00:46:04.240
[Guest]: If a nuclear war were to break out, even though it's improbable, but it could do such tremendous

00:46:04.240 --> 00:46:07.960
[Guest]: damage that it could cancel out all of the incremental advances.

00:46:07.960 --> 00:46:12.880
[Guest]: It's been said that if India and Pakistan had a full-fledged nuclear war that could

00:46:12.880 --> 00:46:18.080
[Guest]: send enough debris and soot into the atmosphere to cause a period of cooling that could lead

00:46:18.080 --> 00:46:22.560
[Guest]: to mass famine and crop failure.

00:46:22.560 --> 00:46:29.000
[Guest]: There could be pandemics, there could be cyber terrorism or cyber sabotage, there may be

00:46:29.000 --> 00:46:36.240
[Guest]: vulnerabilities of the system that we don't yet understand that could be exploited.

00:46:36.240 --> 00:46:42.400
[Guest]: And it could be that the future belongs to Donald Trump and Vladimir Putin and Viktor

00:46:42.400 --> 00:46:45.680
[Guest]: Orban rather than to the world's liberal Democrats.

00:46:45.680 --> 00:46:48.680
[Amit Varma]: Thank you for that very bleak vision, you should have called your book Enlightenment

00:46:48.680 --> 00:46:49.680
[Amit Varma]: Never.

00:46:49.680 --> 00:46:51.600
[Amit Varma]: Thanks so much for coming on the show, Stephen.

00:46:51.600 --> 00:46:54.320
[Amit Varma]: Thank you.

00:46:54.320 --> 00:46:58.200
[Amit Varma]: If you enjoyed listening to the show, do head on over to your nearest bookstore and pick

00:46:58.200 --> 00:47:00.480
